The Experimental Design Eight groups of Tribolium confusa beetles were exposed to different concentrations of carbon disulphide for 5 hours.

#This data set looks at continuous variables (beetle mortality rate and dose of carbon disulphide). The data has a normal distribution and passes the Shapiro-Wilk test for normality (p>.05) and also shows a normal distribution in the QQ-plots. Since we are comparing two normal continuous variables, a Gaussian linear regression was chosen as the model. The link function used for Gaussian models is "identity". The p-values for both the intercept(1st group dose) and the given groups (remaining doses) is <.05, suggesting that there is a significant difference. The null hypothesis is rejected, the alternative (correlation/strong relationship between survival and dosage) is accepted. Residual deviance is low, meaning that the predicted values of the model are close to the actual values.

Problem 2 - Plant Diversity experiment

Background and Question The plant diversity data.csvfile contains data for counts of the number of species of plants counted in experimental grassland plots. In grassland systems fertilization often increases productivity of plants, but also leads to a loss of plant species diversity. One hypothesis about why this occurs is that because fertilization leads to enhanced growth (higher productivity) that it creates asymmetric competition for light (taller plants shade out shorter ones) which reduces diversity. This experiment tests this hypothesis by adding supplemental light to the understory (shaded) plants.

The Experimental Design The design is a fully crossed design of two factors: 1) fertilization treatment (F) + or - and 2) addition of light (L) + or -.

Specific Question

Determine whether there is a loss of species with fertilization and the effects of light supplementation.

plants<-read.csv("~/GitHub/Plant diversity data.csv",stringsAsFactors=FALSE)
head(plants)
plants2 <- plants
fert <- plants2$Fertilizer
fert2 = replicate(32,0)
for (i in 1:32) {
  thisVal = fert[i]
  if (thisVal =="F-") {
    fert2[i] = 0
  }
  else{
    fert2[i] = 1
  }
}
plants2$Fertilizer <- fert2

light = plants2$Light
light2 = replicate(32,0)
for (i in 1:32) {
  thisVal = light[i]
  if (thisVal =="L-") {
    light2[i] = 0
  }
  else{
    light2[i] = 1
  }
}
plants2$Light <- light2
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(plants2, aes(x = Fertilizer, y = Diversity, colour = Light)) + 
    geom_point(size = 2) + 
    labs(x = "Fertilizer", y = "Diversity") + 
    theme_classic()+geom_jitter(size=2,height=.1,width=0.1,alpha=0.5)+
geom_smooth(method = "loess", size = 1, col = "black", se = FALSE) + labs(x = "Fertilizer", y = "Diversity") +  theme_classic()

#In question 2, we are looking at counts of species as an indicator of species diversity in response to presence of light and presence of fertilizer. Fertilizer and light were transformed from presence/absence data to binomial values (0=absent, 1=present). Since the data is discrete and binary, a binomial model is used with the link function "logit". The p-values are greater than .05 for diversity and fertilizer, meaning that there is no significant difference between diversity and the presence/absence of fertilizer. The null hypothesis is supported (fertilizer does not have an effect on diversity). The residual deviance is around 40, suggesting that there is a difference in the predicted model outcome data and the actual data. The p-values for diversity and light are <.05, meaning that there is a significant difference in species counts and presence/absence of additional light in the understory.

Problem 3 - Number of parasites on fish

Background The data file Fish_parasites.csv contains data for the number of parasites counted on fish that were sampled from a creek at 20 sites located at different distances from cooling towers of a nuclear power plant. The goal of the study was to determine if the elevated temperatures from cooling tower effluent affected parasite prevalence and virulence in fish. Although it was not part of the original sampling design, the researchers discovered that there was an additional and potentially confounding variable that differred among sitessalinity. The researchers noted the salinity of each site in their data file by classifying each site as being either high or low salinity.

Specific Question Determine whether the abundance of parasites increases with distance from power plants and to what extent does salinity influence those effects.

fish<-read.csv("~/GitHub/Fish_parasites.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
head(fish)
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(fish, aes(x = distance, y = counts, colour = salinity)) + 
    geom_point(size = 1) + 
    labs(x = "Distance", y = "Counts") + 
    theme_classic()+geom_jitter(size=1,height=.1,width=0.1,alpha=0.5)+
geom_smooth(method = "loess", size = 1, col = "black", se = FALSE) + labs(x = "Distance", y = "Counts") +  theme_classic()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

cat<- glm(counts ~ distance+salinity, family = poisson(link = "log"), data = fish)


visreg(cat, xvar = "distance")

visreg(cat, xvar = "salinity", rug = FALSE); points(jitter(counts, 0.2) ~ distance, data = fish, pch = 1, 
    col = "firebrick", lwd = 1.5)

#In question 3, we are observing parasite numbers on fish in response to salinity and also vicinity to cooling towers of nuclear plants. Since the data is discrete (counts), the Poisson model with link function "log" is used. P-values are all <.05, showing significant differences between distance and parasite counts, salinity and parasite counts and salinity and distance. The null hypothesis (no sig. diff. btwn distance and parasites, salinity and parasites is rejected). By observing the graph that plots salinity levels and distance across counts, it is suggested that low salinity accounts for higher parasite levels on fish. Increased distance from the towers also results in an increase in parasites on fish. The residual deviance is high, meaning that the predicted model outcomes vary greatly from the actual outcomes.
